Learning Creative Learning \'96 reimagining creative learning for the web. \
\
\pard\pardeftab720

\b0\fs24 \cf0 Many Universities have experimented with MOOCs as a way of delivering content to large groups. But what happens when a grad school course is opened up for free online, with a  deliberately non-MOOC structure?\
\
\
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298

\b\fs36 \cf0 What We Did\
\pard\pardeftab720

\b0\fs24 \cf0 \
\
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240
\cf0 Learning Creative Learning is a graduate course on learning technologies that has been running in the MIT Media Lab for several years.  Taught by Mitch Resnick from the Lifelong Kindergarten Group, it\'92s traditionally been targeted primarily at a small group of students from the MIT Media Lab and Harvard Graduate School of Education. The course runs over 11 weeks, and covers topics such as Social Creativity, Motivation and Persistence, and Constructionism and Making. \
In February 2013, P2PU and the team at the Lifelong Kindergarten decided to conduct a giant experiment - we wanted to tinker with the MOOC model, and see if it was possible to still learn in a socially connected way, and work on smaller projects within a large online course, rather than passively absorb lectures. Might we be able, we asked ourselves, to transfer the small, intimate, interactive experience online, and preserve it even if thousands or tens of thousands of people signed up?  So we decided to run Learning Creative Learning online, at the same time as it ran in real life. We made sure it was free, easy to access, and invited the world to sign up.\
One thing everyone realised fairly early on was that there was no blueprint for how to do this. While many institutions have opened up their courseware, or run MOOCs, nobody had tried to integrate an online and offline community in quite the same way, or designed the courses with the objective of facilitating personal interaction.  The first question was how to adapt the content, which is usually designed to be taught as a small seminar and project-based course with 15-25 students. Without a clear idea of who would be signing up (teachers? students? technologists? firefighters?) the final decision was to adapt how materials were presented, and how interaction was encouraged, rather than re-creating content. In order to keep access as easy as possible, and keep development costs down, the course didn\'92t have custom platforms or portals, but used open source software and tools that are freely available on the web. 
\b \

\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720
\cf0 \
\
\
