\pard\pardeftab720\sa298

\b\fs36 \cf0 Reflections\
\pard\pardeftab720

\b0\fs24 \cf0 \
\
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240
\cf0 This experiment involved transferring the experience of a small, specialist, university course into an massive, open, online experience. However, we learned many lessons that would be of interest more broadly, to anyone looking to transfer an existing course into an online environment. In every experiment, some results are more immediately clear than others. In Learning Creative Learning, managing the question of transfer, or how something learnt in one context can be used in another, was a challenge - just as it is in face-to-face learning. Current research on the subject shows that transfer happens most often if people are explicitly engaged in thinking about the transfer while they learn. In order to facilitate this, at the beginning of each of the video sessions, online participants were asked to share what they had come up with in the previous week, which allowed people to show how they were transferring their learning, but also encouraged interactivity within the group. There was a lot of discussion about taking risks, experimenting, failure and motivation and many of the participants reported back that these conversations helped them to rethink their classes, or projects they were doing themselves as teachers.  \
\
\
Unlike many online courses, Learning Creative Learning was designed to allow people to finish with a portfolio of work, rather than a certificate of completion. Portfolios offer more nuanced and in-depth presentations of learning. But in many ways, it was the unexpected results that made the course rewarding for the organisers and the participants alike. At education conferences throughout the year, people have been meeting up face-to-face as a result of the course, and these lasting relationships defy the MOOC model. The post-course activity has also been surprising. Italian participants organised a makers fair, and the Google Plus community is still active. For many teachers, working in environments where budgets are being cut and innovation is discouraged, the community is not simply community for the sake of it, but also about holding on to their vision of what is possible in education, and sharing their struggles with others.\
\
Making the case for the value of large online courses, particularly within institutions that are often seen as being part of the ivory tower establishment, and where a lot of the rhetoric takes the form of "we're going to teach the rest of the world" can be difficult. But this course has shown that there is value in opening up, engaging with communities and learning from them. \
\
The course will run again in the Spring semester of 2014, and  we\'92re already thinking about how to make improvements. The live video sessions were stressful for those who were speaking, and talking to people in the room and online sometimes left speakers unsure of who they were speaking to. We\'92re already working on new technology which will allow us to mitigate this. The plan is also to allow participants to self-organise a little more, and form their own groups using a variety of tools.  \
\
As a proof-of-concept, Learning Creative Learning did what it set out to, proving that university-level, seminar-style courses can be opened up and taught face-to-face and online simultaneously. But more than that, it was an experiment in community building between online and offline learning communities, which, depending on one\'92s perspective either broke the MOOC model, or, as we like to think, fixed it. \
